<p><strong>招生要求 </strong></p>
<ul>
<li>招收 10，11，12年级学生</li>
<li>TOEFL (90+）</li>
<li>MAP测试成绩单</li>
<li>国际学校成绩单</li>
<li>或其他英语能力证明</li>
<li>电话15601221714，微信公众号：英语学分课</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>6</strong></p>
<p><strong>课程大纲 </strong></p>
<p>This AP® English Language &amp; Composition course is a virtual course, which meets through threaded discussion, as opposed to “real time” discussions/meetings. Students work independently, collaboratively in small groups, and as a whole class, as well as one on one with the teacher, all through discussion threads devoted to these activities. The course is 33 weeks long, with a Wednesday through Tuesday course week. The syllabus is divided into quarters, with overarching themes for semester one and semester two.</p>
<p>Weeks 1-8</p>
<p>Introduction to Rhetoric, Style, &amp; Language</p>
<p>Text: Excerpts from Bird by Bird by Ann Lamott and various other supplemental readings</p>
<p>In weeks 1-4, Aristotle’s Rhetorical Triangle will be featured as the primary analytical tool, and students will practice identifying different appeals in non-fiction writing. Students discuss Anne Lamott’s view on first drafts, practice writing techniques designed to eliminate writer’s block, and identify rhetorical situations in a variety of different writings. Weeks 5 and 6 focus on style, the use of specific word and sentence choices that shape the author’s message by creating the tone. They identify several grammar and punctuation resources and read several classic essays about punctuation, discover a set of writer’s toolbox tools to help in the writing process, and look closer at the idea of tone in writing. The primary focus of Week 7 will be on using a summary/analysis tool called the rhetorical précis: a 4-sentence paragraph that precisely and concisely addresses the rhetorical situation and strategy in a given essay.</p>
<p>Activities in weeks 1-8 will focus on the following objectives:</p>
<ul>
<li>Learn the basic definition and terminology used in the study of rhetoric</li>
<li>Identify examples of each of the five (5) rhetorical situation components by comparing/contrasting different readings.</li>
<li>Practice identifying different "appeals" in non-fiction writing</li>
<li>Use the reading reduction as a method of improving reading comprehension.</li>
<li>Develop "Writer's Toolbox" techniques for becoming better writers</li>
<li>Learn to both recognize and develop greater context in writing</li>
<li>Identify examples of each of the five (5) rhetorical situation components by comparing/contrasting different readings.</li>
<li>Practice identifying different "appeals" in non-fiction writing</li>
<li>Use the reading reduction as a method of improving reading comprehension.</li>
<li>Analyze figures of speech, and in particular, tropes and schemes.</li>
<li>Look at different syntactical structures in order to understand their impact on meaning and purpose.</li>
<li>Experiment with different tropes and schemes in order to understand their impact on meaning and purpose.</li>
<li>Identify and discuss the hidden value of punctuation marks.</li>
<li>Use Writer's Workshop techniques to begin or refine the writing process</li>
<li>Write a rhetorical précis</li>
<li>Use all the tools of rhetorical analysis to reflect a deep understanding of why writer's write (purpose), and how they write (rhetorical strategy)</li>
<li>Weeks 9-15</li>
<li>Argumentation</li>
<li>Various Supplementary Readings</li>
<li>In Weeks 9-15, students will look at some actual AP® essay questions, analyze the prompts, and examine the rubric. They will learn about the Toulmin model of argumentative analysis and practice methods for how to respond to open-ended and directed argument prompt questions. Lessons in this term also cover how to effectively use citations when answering prompt questions. Weeks 12 and 13 addresses satire as a specialized form of argument and how to avoid logical fallacies in an argument. In week 15, the unit on argumentation culminates in a series of AP® prompt practices.</li>
<li>Activities in weeks 9-15 will focus on the following objectives:</li>
<li>Understand the differences between "effective" (8), "adequate" (6), and "inadequate" (4) on the 9-point AP® Rubric</li>
<li>Learn the structure of the rhetorical analysis prompt question</li>
<li>Develop a method for how to respond to the rhetorical analysis prompt question</li>
<li>Understand the differences between "effective" (8), "adequate" (6), and "inadequate" (4) on the 9-point AP® Rubric</li>
<li>Learn how to contextualize a response to a rhetorical analysis essay question (often present on 8-9 essays)</li>
<li>Learn how to effectively use citations when answering a prompt questions</li>
<li>Practice timed AP® essay prompt responses</li>
<li>Learn about the Toulmin method of argumentative analysis.</li>
<li>Learn the structure of the open-ended and directed argument prompt questions.</li>
<li>Practice methods for how to respond to the argument prompt questions.</li>
<li>Use the reading reduction as a method of improving reading comprehension.</li>
<li>Identify the six (6) attributes of "argument" by comparing/contrasting different readings.</li>
<li>Use the reading reduction as a method of improving reading comprehension.</li>
<li>Identify examples of each of the three (3) logical appeals of "argument" by comparing/contrasting different readings.</li>
<li>Integrate multiple logical appeals in one essay to achieve purpose.</li>
<li>Critically reflect on rhetorical choices in your own writing.</li>
<li>Practice the 3-Draft approach to writing essays.</li>
<li>Write an argument précis.</li>
<li>Use the reading reduction as a method of improving reading comprehension of satires.</li>
<li>Identify general rhetorical (e.g., purpose, audience) and specific argumentative (e.g., persuasive appeals) by comparing/contrasting different satires.</li>
<li>Understand the need to avoid logical fallacies when writing arguments.</li>
<li>Write a cohesive argument.</li>
<li>Weeks 16-18</li>
<li>Synthesis and Visual Literacy</li>
<li>Texts: Fast Food Nation</li>
<li>Various Supplementary Readings</li>
<li>In weeks, 16-18, student will read, discuss and research Eric Schlosser's New York Times 2001 Bestseller, Fast Food Nation. They will use the book to evaluate arguments and practice writing arguments. They will also evaluate political cartoons using the Library of Congress website, look at the role of advertisements directed at children, and examine the role of logical fallacies in influencing audiences in advertising.</li>
<li>Activities in weeks 16-18 will focus on the following objectives:</li>
<li>Demonstrate an understanding of the "art of argument" by presenting an effective argument in brief.</li>
<li>Use the reading reduction as a method of improving reading comprehension of political cartoons.</li>
<li>Identify five (5) persuasive techniques used in political cartoons - Symbolism, Exaggeration, Labeling, Analogy, Irony - and use them in comparing/contrasting different cartoons.</li>
<li>Use the reading reduction as a method of improving reading comprehension of advertisements directed at children.</li>
<li>Understand the role of logical fallacies in influencing audiences by comparing/contrasting different advertisements.</li>
<li>Synthesize ideas from multiple sources into a cohesive argument.</li>
<li>Critically evaluate source material.</li>
<li>Write a synthesis argument essay using multiple sources</li>
<li>Weeks 19-20</li>
<li>Argument: Research (Nonviolent Protests) and Visual Literacy</li>
<li>Text: Various Supplemental Readings</li>
<li>In weeks 19 and 20, students apply the Aristotle Rhetorical Triangle to visual works. In addition, they will conduct primary research to write a five page argument about nonviolent protests in history.</li>
<li>Activities in weeks 19-20 will focus on the following objectives:</li>
<li>Analyze selected paintings and photos for visual literacy.Use the reading reduction as a method of improving reading comprehension.</li>
<li>Analyze different paintings &amp; photos for rhetorical structure</li>
<li>Select a nonviolent protest topic, find some online sources, and write an annotated bibliography.</li>
<li>Identify examples of visual attributes by comparing/contrasting different paintings and photos.</li>
<li>Gather relevant information from multiple authoritative print and digital sources, using advanced searches effectively; assess the strengths and limitations of each source in terms of the task, purpose, and audience; integrate information into the text selectively to maintain the flow of ideas, avoiding plagiarism and over reliance on any one source and following a standard format for citation.</li>
<li>Conduct primary research to support an argument.</li>
<li>Weeks 21 – 22</li>
<li>Argument: Annotated Bibliography, Endnotes, Footnotes, and Visual Literacy</li>
<li>Text: Various Supplemental Readings</li>
<li>Week 21-22 continue the concept of including visual works to construct arguments by focusing on charts and graphs. Students will review the use of footnotes and endnotes in writing and analyze an essay by David Foster Wallace. They will continue with practice for the AP® multiple choice test and write a researched argument essay using multiple authoritative print and digital sources.</li>
<li>Activities in weeks 21-22 will focus on the following objectives:</li>
<li>Use the reading reduction as a method of improving reading comprehension of charts &amp; graphs.</li>
<li>Conduct online research, integrate visual elements, and conduct primary (original) research of their own - usually, a survey or interview to support an argument.</li>
<li>Gather relevant information from multiple authoritative print and digital sources, using advanced searches effectively; assess the strengths and limitations of each source in terms of the task, purpose, and audience; integrate information into the text selectively to maintain the flow of ideas, avoiding plagiarism and over reliance on any one source and following a standard format for citation.</li>
<li>Review the use of footnotes in writing.</li>
<li>Analyze an essay by David Foster Wallace's for footnote and endnote use.</li>
<li>Write a researched argument essay using multiple authoritative print and digital sources</li>
<li>Weeks 23</li>
<li>Argument: AP® Synthesis Prompts and Argument Prompts</li>
<li>Texts: Various Supplemental Readings</li>
<li>In weeks 23-25, students will review synthesis prompts on the AP® Exam, discuss how to approach a synthesis essay, and practice with timed AP® prompts. They will create a graphic organizer as a guideline for approaching the synthesis essay question and practice creating a synthesis essay prompt with a partner. Finally, they will return to Argument essays *without* Sources, and practice timed AP® essay prompt responses to these as well.</li>
<li>Activities in week 23 will focus on the following objectives:</li>
<li>Use graphic organizers as a writing strategy to help organize writing ideas.</li>
<li>Use technology within the content area to communicate ideas, gather and synthesize information, and to communicate knowledge.</li>
<li>Practice timed AP® essay prompt responses.</li>
<li>Use a Web 2.0 Graphic Organizer to create a guideline to approach answering the synthesis essay question.</li>
<li>Create a synthesis essay prompt question.</li>
<li>Week 26</li>
<li>Argument: Historic Speeches</li>
<li>Texts: Various Supplemental Readings</li>
<li>In week 26, students analyze the rhetorical style and argument strategies of famous political orators. They practice emulating these orators and using diction and syntax to create tone in their argumentative writing.</li>
<li>Activities in week 26 will focus on the following objectives:</li>
<li>Analyze famous political speeches for rhetorical and argumentative strategies.</li>
<li>Practice imitating the rhetorical style of famous political orators.</li>
<li>Use the reading reduction as a method of improving reading comprehension.</li>
<li>Use diction and syntax to create tone in argumentative writing.</li>
<li>Week 27</li>
<li>Argument: Fiction</li>
<li>Texts: Supplemental Readings by James Joyce</li>
<li>Week 27 concentrates on analyzing the rhetorical strategies used in fiction. Students examine a short story by James Joyce and write a two page essay examining his strategies.</li>
<li>Activities in week 27 will focus on the following objectives:</li>
<li>Use the reading reduction as a method of improving reading comprehension.</li>
<li>Combine both strategy and style in one essay to achieve purpose.</li>
<li>Critically reflect on rhetorical choices in your own writing.</li>
<li>Practice the 3-Draft approach to writing essays.</li>
<li>Weeks 28-33</li>
<li>The last six weeks of the course are dedicated to AP® Test Prep. Students complete several multiple choice tests and essay responses to AP® essay prompts for practice. The look for patterns in questions from the past decade and discuss patterns with classmates. They share techniques to prepare for the exam and take a full essay test and a recently released multiple choice test.</li>
</ul>
